00:38:05.713 --> 00:38:09.070 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You have a free
resource for police officers

00:38:09.070 --> 00:38:12.800 align:middle line:84%
and first responders that they
can take a free online class

00:38:12.800 --> 00:38:14.150 align:middle line:90%
at the website.

00:38:14.150 --> 00:38:15.410 align:middle line:90%
What is the website again?

00:38:15.410 --> 00:38:17.118 align:middle line:84%
>>WIMBERGER:
Neurosculptinginstitute.com.

00:38:17.118 --> 00:38:17.618 align:middle line:90%


00:38:17.618 --> 00:38:19.490 align:middle line:84%
And I've also put
this video on YouTube.

00:38:19.490 --> 00:38:21.870 align:middle line:84%
It's a free stress
management class

00:38:21.870 --> 00:38:24.120 align:middle line:84%
for emotional
survival for officers.

00:38:24.120 --> 00:38:25.240 align:middle line:90%
It's an hour long.

00:38:25.240 --> 00:38:26.860 align:middle line:84%
And our mission at
the Institute is

00:38:26.860 --> 00:38:30.620 align:middle line:84%
to get resources to officers
outside of the agency

00:38:30.620 --> 00:38:34.650 align:middle line:84%
so that they can come and
feel safe in their processing.

00:38:34.650 --> 00:38:36.420 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Now, what
about all others,

00:38:36.420 --> 00:38:38.550 align:middle line:84%
about civilians that
have stress and that

00:38:38.550 --> 00:38:40.190 align:middle line:90%
need to learn resilience?

00:38:40.190 --> 00:38:42.250 align:middle line:84%
And we need to teach
ourselves new stories

00:38:42.250 --> 00:38:44.660 align:middle line:90%
and retrain our neuroplasticity.

00:38:44.660 --> 00:38:46.292 align:middle line:90%
How do you teach us to do that?

00:38:46.292 --> 00:38:48.750 align:middle line:84%
>>WIMBERGER: I invite you to
the Institute to take classes.

00:38:48.750 --> 00:38:51.240 align:middle line:84%
I invite you to look at all
the resources we have online.

00:38:51.240 --> 00:38:53.360 align:middle line:84%
We also have a
robust free library

00:38:53.360 --> 00:38:55.594 align:middle line:84%
of neuroscience
articles for people

00:38:55.594 --> 00:38:56.885 align:middle line:90%
who want to educate themselves.

00:38:56.885 --> 00:38:58.010 align:middle line:90%


00:38:58.010 --> 00:38:59.470 align:middle line:90%
And we do that there.

00:38:59.470 --> 00:39:02.350 align:middle line:84%
And we also have a team of
certified neurosculpting

00:39:02.350 --> 00:39:06.060 align:middle line:84%
facilitators who take this
work out to other venues

00:39:06.060 --> 00:39:08.380 align:middle line:84%
and are spreading it
around the country.

00:39:08.380 --> 00:39:10.390 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Can you teach
me a few tips when

00:39:10.390 --> 00:39:13.370 align:middle line:84%
I get into a place of
extreme stress or I--

00:39:13.370 --> 00:39:15.460 align:middle line:90%
so I can circumvent that stress.

00:39:15.460 --> 00:39:16.210 align:middle line:90%
>>WIMBERGER: Yeah.

00:39:16.210 --> 00:39:18.940 align:middle line:84%
I would say that
if you're in it,

00:39:18.940 --> 00:39:20.600 align:middle line:84%
you're in the
middle of a stress,

00:39:20.600 --> 00:39:24.540 align:middle line:84%
the first thing is to
name what you feel.

00:39:24.540 --> 00:39:30.100 align:middle line:84%
So rather than say I am angry--
When you say I am angry,

00:39:30.100 --> 00:39:33.310 align:middle line:84%
you are accessing a very
particular part of the brain.

00:39:33.310 --> 00:39:36.950 align:middle line:84%
When you change the verb
to feel, I feel angry,

00:39:36.950 --> 00:39:39.800 align:middle line:84%
you have activity that
migrates to a different part

00:39:39.800 --> 00:39:43.300 align:middle line:84%
of the brain, which then starts
to down regulate your stress

00:39:43.300 --> 00:39:44.070 align:middle line:90%
response.

00:39:44.070 --> 00:39:46.420 align:middle line:84%
So there's a power in
changing that verb.

00:39:46.420 --> 00:39:50.980 align:middle line:84%
There is a neurological change
when you change the verb.

00:39:50.980 --> 00:39:56.420 align:middle line:84%
So I would immediately go to I
am angry to I'm feeling angry.

00:39:56.420 --> 00:39:57.490 align:middle line:90%
That's the first thing.

00:39:57.490 --> 00:40:00.820 align:middle line:84%
I would start doing some deep
breathing, in through the nose

00:40:00.820 --> 00:40:03.029 align:middle line:84%
and out as much as
possible, because you're

00:40:03.029 --> 00:40:04.695 align:middle line:84%
going to start
mitigating that response.

00:40:04.695 --> 00:40:05.800 align:middle line:90%


00:40:05.800 --> 00:40:09.890 align:middle line:84%
Third, I would shake
wildly, because you

00:40:09.890 --> 00:40:13.890 align:middle line:84%
don't want to freeze
around the idea

00:40:13.890 --> 00:40:17.000 align:middle line:84%
and repeat it so that
it's in this echo chamber.

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:19.100 align:middle line:84%
Your muscles will
start to contract

00:40:19.100 --> 00:40:20.660 align:middle line:90%
in this stress response.

00:40:20.660 --> 00:40:23.320 align:middle line:84%
You don't want to
maintain that contraction

00:40:23.320 --> 00:40:25.050 align:middle line:90%
unless you need to use it.

00:40:25.050 --> 00:40:27.050 align:middle line:84%
But if this is a
thought, you want

00:40:27.050 --> 00:40:30.460 align:middle line:84%
to shake it in a
very wild manner

00:40:30.460 --> 00:40:33.735 align:middle line:84%
and start dissipating the levels
of adrenaline and cortisol

00:40:33.735 --> 00:40:35.205 align:middle line:84%
that are now amped
in your system.

00:40:35.205 --> 00:40:35.830 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Uh huh.

00:40:35.830 --> 00:40:37.360 align:middle line:90%
That whole chemical cascade.

00:40:37.360 --> 00:40:38.480 align:middle line:90%
>>WIMBERGER: Yes.

00:40:38.480 --> 00:40:40.930 align:middle line:84%
Those are some immediate
things you can do.

00:40:40.930 --> 00:40:42.860 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: What about
chronic stress,

00:40:42.860 --> 00:40:45.220 align:middle line:84%
where you keep seeing
that bank balance lower.

00:40:45.220 --> 00:40:48.520 align:middle line:84%
You've gotten let go
of your job and you're

00:40:48.520 --> 00:40:49.830 align:middle line:90%
looking for another job.

00:40:49.830 --> 00:40:51.604 align:middle line:90%
I mean, those chronic stressors.

00:40:51.604 --> 00:40:53.020 align:middle line:84%
>>WIMBERGER: The
chronic stressors

00:40:53.020 --> 00:40:56.460 align:middle line:84%
require you changing the
story and the relationship

00:40:56.460 --> 00:40:57.350 align:middle line:90%
around that.

00:40:57.350 --> 00:41:02.316 align:middle line:84%
So for those chronic--
we would suggest classes,

00:41:02.316 --> 00:41:03.940 align:middle line:84%
taking those introductory
classes where

00:41:03.940 --> 00:41:07.055 align:middle line:84%
we're teaching you that whole
methodical process, where we're

00:41:07.055 --> 00:41:09.680 align:middle line:84%
holding your hand while we walk
you through it so you can start

00:41:09.680 --> 00:41:12.270 align:middle line:84%
doing that at the
end of every day.

00:41:12.270 --> 00:41:15.140 align:middle line:84%
You can start doing that
after you open the bills

00:41:15.140 --> 00:41:18.060 align:middle line:84%
and put them down for
a moment, and create,

00:41:18.060 --> 00:41:21.512 align:middle line:84%
or go into this new
meditative story

00:41:21.512 --> 00:41:22.970 align:middle line:84%
so that your reaction
is different.

00:41:22.970 --> 00:41:24.420 align:middle line:90%
And then go back to the bills.

00:41:24.420 --> 00:41:27.210 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And the new story could
be this is going to work out,

00:41:27.210 --> 00:41:29.130 align:middle line:84%
this is going to be
fine, this is temporary.

00:41:29.130 --> 00:41:30.120 align:middle line:90%
Those types of things?

00:41:30.120 --> 00:41:30.870 align:middle line:90%
>>WIMBERGER: Yeah.

00:41:30.870 --> 00:41:33.589 align:middle line:84%
I would say the new story
needs to be plausible to you.

00:41:33.589 --> 00:41:34.380 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Believable.

00:41:34.380 --> 00:41:35.960 align:middle line:90%
>>WIMBERGER: Believable to you.

00:41:35.960 --> 00:41:39.965 align:middle line:84%
So we don't want to go to the
rose colored glasses extreme.

00:41:39.965 --> 00:41:41.580 align:middle line:90%
We want it to be believable.

00:41:41.580 --> 00:41:44.420 align:middle line:84%
So this is temporary
is a great one.

00:41:44.420 --> 00:41:48.880 align:middle line:84%
Or this moment will pass
just as it always has.

00:41:48.880 --> 00:41:49.860 align:middle line:90%
Something believable.

00:41:49.860 --> 00:41:51.400 align:middle line:90%


00:41:51.400 --> 00:41:54.730 align:middle line:84%
But if you fit that
belief into the structure

00:41:54.730 --> 00:41:58.110 align:middle line:84%
of neurosculpting, then
your brain grabs on to it

00:41:58.110 --> 00:41:59.477 align:middle line:90%
and starts to believe it.

00:41:59.477 --> 00:42:00.310 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:42:00.310 --> 00:42:02.410 align:middle line:84%
And it can help lower
the stress response

00:42:02.410 --> 00:42:03.440 align:middle line:90%
and the chronic stress.

00:42:03.440 --> 00:42:04.940 align:middle line:84%
>>WIMBERGER: And
change the pattern.

00:42:04.940 --> 00:42:07.020 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Now there's
a wonderful girl

00:42:07.020 --> 00:42:09.082 align:middle line:84%
that you worked
with who-- Heather.

00:42:09.082 --> 00:42:10.540 align:middle line:84%
Tell us a little
bit about Heather.

00:42:10.540 --> 00:42:12.070 align:middle line:90%
>>WIMBERGER: Heather is amazing.

00:42:12.070 --> 00:42:15.640 align:middle line:84%
She had an accident
about 11 years ago now.

00:42:15.640 --> 00:42:16.820 align:middle line:90%
She was thrown from a horse.

00:42:16.820 --> 00:42:18.180 align:middle line:90%


00:42:18.180 --> 00:42:22.140 align:middle line:84%
So her last recollection
is grabbing on

00:42:22.140 --> 00:42:24.150 align:middle line:84%
for the last moment
of control, hoping

00:42:24.150 --> 00:42:27.070 align:middle line:84%
to control the head of the
horse and not being able to.

00:42:27.070 --> 00:42:29.940 align:middle line:84%
And then she ended
up crushing her neck,

00:42:29.940 --> 00:42:32.560 align:middle line:84%
and didn't sever
her spine but had

00:42:32.560 --> 00:42:35.640 align:middle line:84%
a subluxation in the
back of her neck,

00:42:35.640 --> 00:42:40.860 align:middle line:84%
ended up a quadriplegic in a
wheelchair, fully assisted.

00:42:40.860 --> 00:42:42.860 align:middle line:84%
So she has a team of
people around the clock who

00:42:42.860 --> 00:42:44.870 align:middle line:84%
have to live with her,
help her out of bed,

00:42:44.870 --> 00:42:46.410 align:middle line:90%
put her in the wheelchair.

00:42:46.410 --> 00:42:49.540 align:middle line:84%
She is a very dynamic
woman and refused

00:42:49.540 --> 00:42:53.350 align:middle line:90%
to take that as her prognosis.

00:42:53.350 --> 00:42:58.420 align:middle line:84%
So she ended up doing a lot
of her own self therapy,

00:42:58.420 --> 00:43:01.450 align:middle line:84%
getting an adaptive yoga
teacher, getting put in a pool,

00:43:01.450 --> 00:43:02.600 align:middle line:90%
swimming, going to the gym.

00:43:02.600 --> 00:43:04.010 align:middle line:90%
They move her limbs.

00:43:04.010 --> 00:43:07.470 align:middle line:84%
And in that time, she
gained movement in her arms.

00:43:07.470 --> 00:43:13.220 align:middle line:84%
So when I met her last
year, paralyzed in her hands

00:43:13.220 --> 00:43:17.240 align:middle line:84%
and unable to
walk, and she asked

00:43:17.240 --> 00:43:21.060 align:middle line:84%
if I would work with her to help
raise money for her therapy.

00:43:21.060 --> 00:43:24.190 align:middle line:84%
And she asked me to
speak at an event.

00:43:24.190 --> 00:43:26.330 align:middle line:84%
And I said I'd
rather work with you.

00:43:26.330 --> 00:43:29.890 align:middle line:84%
So I took her on as
a pro bono client.

00:43:29.890 --> 00:43:31.770 align:middle line:84%
And we've been working
together since.

00:43:31.770 --> 00:43:34.200 align:middle line:84%
And we've been
using neurosculpting

00:43:34.200 --> 00:43:38.090 align:middle line:84%
to have her enhance
the plasticity

00:43:38.090 --> 00:43:40.750 align:middle line:90%
of her motor and sensory cortex.

00:43:40.750 --> 00:43:43.580 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So she creates a
new story in her brain.

00:43:43.580 --> 00:43:45.830 align:middle line:84%
>>WIMBERGER: She down
regulates her stress,

00:43:45.830 --> 00:43:50.100 align:middle line:84%
activates the front, creates a
new story in the motor cortex,

00:43:50.100 --> 00:43:53.935 align:middle line:84%
specifically in the cortex area
that controls hand movement.

00:43:53.935 --> 00:43:55.060 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Does she visualize?

00:43:55.060 --> 00:43:56.005 align:middle line:84%
>>WIMBERGER: She
visualizes this.

00:43:56.005 --> 00:43:56.500 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Moving.

00:43:56.500 --> 00:43:56.860 align:middle line:90%
I see.

00:43:56.860 --> 00:43:57.140 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:43:57.140 --> 00:43:57.640 align:middle line:90%
Great.

00:43:57.640 --> 00:44:00.190 align:middle line:84%
>>WIMBERGER: And in
that visualization,

00:44:00.190 --> 00:44:04.870 align:middle line:84%
I have her open her
hands in her mind's eye.

00:44:04.870 --> 00:44:07.710 align:middle line:90%
I have her name each finger.

00:44:07.710 --> 00:44:09.530 align:middle line:90%
We spell each finger.

00:44:09.530 --> 00:44:12.250 align:middle line:84%
We have her give
it a personality,

00:44:12.250 --> 00:44:13.770 align:middle line:90%
abstract colors, textures.

00:44:13.770 --> 00:44:17.110 align:middle line:90%
I have her then take that thumb.

00:44:17.110 --> 00:44:21.850 align:middle line:84%
T-H-U-M-B is her thumb, and I
have her send that imagery down

00:44:21.850 --> 00:44:24.010 align:middle line:84%
through her body
into her thumbs.

00:44:24.010 --> 00:44:27.870 align:middle line:84%
We have her do somatic
repetitious identification.

00:44:27.870 --> 00:44:30.830 align:middle line:84%
I then touch her
thumbs and let her

00:44:30.830 --> 00:44:33.150 align:middle line:84%
know what it feels like
for external stimulation.

00:44:33.150 --> 00:44:36.430 align:middle line:84%
And just this summer she
has volitional movement

00:44:36.430 --> 00:44:37.490 align:middle line:90%
in her thumbs.

00:44:37.490 --> 00:44:39.210 align:middle line:90%
She's opened her index fingers.

00:44:39.210 --> 00:44:40.740 align:middle line:90%
She has the pinch motion.

00:44:40.740 --> 00:44:44.390 align:middle line:84%
And just most recently,
she's picked up a rock

00:44:44.390 --> 00:44:46.121 align:middle line:84%
and transferred it
to her other hand.

00:44:46.121 --> 00:44:47.870 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Oh, we get to
see a video of that.

00:44:47.870 --> 00:44:51.785 align:middle line:84%
Take a look at this video of
Lisa working with Heather.

